        <Book ISBN="978-0262033848" id="B1">
            <Title><![CDATA[Learning XML & JSON]]></Title>
            <Author><![CDATA[Asaad Mansour]]></Author>
            <Preface><![CDATA[This preface explains the goals: demonstrate XML structure, attributes, CDATA, and parsing examples. Special characters like <, >, & are shown.]]></Preface>
            <Part>
                <Title><![CDATA[Part I: Basics]]></Title>
                <Chapter>
                    <Title><![CDATA[Getting Started]]></Title>
                    <Summary><![CDATA[Introduces elements, attributes, and CDATA.]]></Summary>
                    <Section>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[XML stands for eXtensible Markup Language. It stores data in a hierarchical form.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Use attributes for small metadata like ISBN or id.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Example characters: <tag>, &amp;, and "quotes" â€” CDATA protects them.]]></Paragraph>
                    </Section>
                    <Section>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Sections group paragraphs.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Elements can be nested arbitrarily.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Remember to keep XML well-formed.]]></Paragraph>
                    </Section>
                </Chapter>
                <Chapter>
                    <Title><![CDATA[XML vs JSON]]></Title>
                    <Summary><![CDATA[Compares XML and JSON structures and use-cases.]]></Summary>
                    <Section>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[JSON is lighter for data interchange.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[XML is better for documents with mixed content.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Both have parsers available in many languages.]]></Paragraph>
                    </Section>
                    <Section>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Converting between them requires mapping elements and attributes.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[CDATA sections are XML-specific.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Use attributes sparingly for identifiers.]]></Paragraph>
                    </Section>
                </Chapter>
            </Part>
            <Part>
                <Title><![CDATA[Part II: Advanced]]></Title>
                <Chapter>
                    <Title><![CDATA[Namespaces & Schemas]]></Title>
                    <Summary><![CDATA[Shows namespaces, DTDs, and XML Schema basics.]]></Summary>
                    <Section>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Namespaces avoid name collisions.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Schemas validate structure.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[DTD is older; XSD is more expressive.]]></Paragraph>
                    </Section>
                    <Section>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Validation helps prevent malformed documents.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Use tools to validate XML files.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Keep schema definitions versioned.]]></Paragraph>
                    </Section>
                </Chapter>
                <Chapter>
                    <Title><![CDATA[Practical Examples]]></Title>
                    <Summary><![CDATA[Real-world transformations and XPath queries.]]></Summary>
                    <Section>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Use XSLT to transform XML to HTML.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[XPath selects nodes efficiently.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Combine tools for pipelines.]]></Paragraph>
                    </Section>
                    <Section>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[Store identifiers in attributes for compactness.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[CDATA sections let you include unescaped markup.]]></Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph><![CDATA[This completes the sample book content.]]></Paragraph>
                    </Section>
                </Chapter>
            </Part>
